    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, I apologize for the sudden goblin detour! It was just a little metaphorical slip of the tongue, but I'm afraid I can't help but think of them when talking about stubborn parts.\n\nTo answer your question about the stuck stem: If the stem is really seized up and won't budge with just a wrench, you'll need to apply a little penetrating oil (like WD-40) to the threads and let it sit for a while. You might also need to use a larger wrench or a pipe wrench to get a better grip, being careful not to strip the threads. If it's still stuck, you might need to gently tap the wrench with a hammer to loosen it up, but be very careful not to damage the faucet body.\n\nOnce the stem is loose enough to turn, you can unscrew the handle, remove the old washer, and install the new one. Just make sure to tighten the nut back on securely so the new washer doesn't fall out or leak again. If you're still having trouble, it might be worth calling a professional plumber, as they have specialized tools that can handle even the most stubborn fixtures.",
