    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, excellent question! While the washer is the usual culprit for a dripping faucet, there are indeed other components that can cause trouble, and it's wise to inspect them all while the faucet is apart.\n\nFirst, check the **O-ring** on the stem. This is a small rubber ring that sits just above the washer. If this O-ring is cracked, flattened, or missing, water will leak past it even if the washer is perfect. It's like a goblin trying to squeeze through a tiny hole in a wall; if the hole is too big or the goblin is too big, the seal fails. You'll need a new O-ring that matches the size of the stem.\n\nNext, look at the **spring** that holds the stem in place. Sometimes the spring gets corroded or loses its tension, making the stem hard to turn or causing it to stay partially open. If the spring is weak, you might need to replace it with a new one to ensure the handle returns to the \"off\" position firmly.\n\nFinally, don't forget the **seat** itself. The seat is the metal surface the washer presses against to stop the water. Over time, this seat can get pitted or corroded",
